This pillow case is made up of six of these

00:01:08.860 --> 00:01:15.860
pinwheel blocks. Each block is made up of
six 5 inch squares. First decide how you want

00:01:16.030 --> 00:01:21.700
your entire pillow case to look like. Each
block has four squares as the base and four

00:01:21.700 --> 00:01:26.860
“blades” (each blade is half a square)
of the pinwheel. Now that you know how you

00:01:26.860 --> 00:01:33.860
want it laid out. Let’s make each block.
All right looking good next step.

00:01:34.330 --> 00:01:38.119
Take the two squares that will make the four
blades of the pinwheel and cut in them in

00:01:38.119 --> 00:01:45.119
half, diagonally. You should now have four
triangles . Then using an iron son low heat

00:01:45.310 --> 00:01:50.700
fold the triangles in half (with wrong sides
together) and press ( you might want to use

00:01:50.700 --> 00:01:57.700
a pressing cloth for this).
Ok looking good next step

00:02:01.020 --> 00:02:06.240
Layout your pinwheel. Place one blade on each
block with the longest side of the triangle

00:02:06.240 --> 00:02:11.219
lining up with the edge of the square it’s
sitting on. Make sure all the blades are pointing

00:02:11.219 --> 00:02:17.450
in the same direction. Note: On of the exposed
edges of the blade will be raw – since we

00:02:17.450 --> 00:02:22.419
are working with a knit fabric it’s fine.
Pin and baste each blade to the square it

00:02:22.419 --> 00:02:29.419
sits on using a slightly less than .5 inch
seam allowance. Then using a .5 inch seam

00:02:32.129 --> 00:02:39.129
allowance, sew two of the squares together
to form a row, twice, then sew the two rows

00:02:53.629 --> 00:03:00.629
together to sew a block. Trim seam bulk in
the center, and making sure blades are laying

00:03:04.159 --> 00:03:09.299
in the correct direction, sew on the center
button. Repeat five more times to make a total

00:03:09.299 --> 00:03:14.389
of six blocks.
Now the rule of the day is Pin. When in doubt

00:03:14.389 --> 00:03:19.409
put in another pin. You just need to use lots
of pins. When it comes to this . And something

00:03:19.409 --> 00:03:24.290
that I found that worked really well is especially
on the really bulky seams that you have to

00:03:24.290 --> 00:03:28.819
go accross - if you put a pin on each side
of the seam. Like rright next to it, it helps

00:03:28.819 --> 00:03:35.819
it line up a lot easier. So just a trick I
learned. Then, Sew the blocks together.

